<div class="slide">
<h1>AJAX</h1>
<h2>Is it Just a Buzz Word?</h2>
<h3>Bryan Mills</h3>
<h4>University of Pittsburgh</h4>
</div>


<div class="slide">
<h1>What is AJAX?</h1>
<ul>
<li><strong>A</strong>synchronous <strong>J</strong>avascript
<strong>A</strong>nd <strong>X</strong>ml</li>
<li>Term coined by <a
href="http://www.adaptivepath.com/publications/essays/archives/000385.php"
title="Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications">Jesse James Garrett</a>
in Early 2005</a></li>
<li>Encompasses several technologies</li>
<li>Enables the creation of dynamic Web Applications</li>
<li>It has and will continue to change the face of the Web</li>
</ul>
<div class="handout">
<ul>
<li>Term only a year old</li>
<li>Like LAMP made up of several technologies</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Why should you care?</h1>
<ul>
<li>Amazon lists over 90 books published on AJAX</li>
<li>Jobs: <a href="http://www.indeed.com/jobs?q=ajax">Indeed</a> lists
over 3500 jobs with the term 'ajax'</li>
<li>Web applications have continued to penetrate virtually all
application spaces</li>
<li>AJAX enables Dynamic User Interfaces via the Web</li>
<li>More Efficient Applications (both in bandwidth and usability)</li>
<li>Yet, another tool in your toolbox</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Who Cares About AJAX</h1>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://maps.google.com/">Google Maps</a>, <a
href="http://www.gmail.com/">Gmail</a></li>
<li><a href="http://amazon.com/">Amazon</a></li>
<li><a href="http://officelive.microsoft.com/">Microsoft</a> - Office Live</li>
<li><a href="http://flickr.com/">flickr</a></li>
<li><a href="http://salesforce.com/">SalesForce</a></li>
<li><a href="http://netflix.com/">Netflix</a></li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>What is it?</h1>
<ul>
<li>Combination of Technologies</li>
<ol>
<li>Web Standards (html and css)</li>
<li>Document Object Model (DOM) Scripting</li>
<li>XMLHttpRequest object enabling Javascript to make Asynchronous
HTTP requests back to the server</li>
<li>Javascript (aka ECMAScript) binding all this together</li>
</ol>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Whats it look like?</h1>
<img src="img/ajax-model.png"/>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Is this stuff new?</h1>
<ul>
<li> Not at All! </li>
<li>Javascript dates back to the early days of Netscape</li>
<li>DOM scripting starting in the late 1990's (see DHTML)</li>
<li>XMLHttpRequest is a bit more recent (last 2 years or so -
Microsoft actually had a similar structure available in 1999)</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Why all the buzz?</h1>
<ul>
<li>Major Sites using the technology</li>
<li>Users more accepting of upgrading browsers</li>
<li>It has a name</li>
<li>Architecture Patterns being identified and written about</li>
<li>Browsers becoming standards compliant</li> 
<li>Frameworks being built to enable ease of implementation</li> 
<li>More and more web-applications</li> 
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Traditional Model</h1>
<ul>
<li>Traditional Web Systems make blocking calls back to
the server</li>
<img src="img/traditionalmodel.gif">
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Asynchronous what?</h1>
<ul>
<li>AJAX enables asynchronous calls by the Client</li>
<li>Allows more interactive sites</li>
<li>Decrease bandwidth, faster response, just plain cool</li>
<img src="img/ajaxmodel.gif">
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>How do we do this?</h1>
<pre>
if (window.XMLHttpRequest) {
    var req = new XMLHttpRequest();
    req.onreadystatechange = requestHandler;
    req.open("GET", "/somefile.xml", true);
    req.send("");
}
function requestHandler() {
    if (req.readyState == 4) { 
       alert(req.statusText);
       req.responseXML.getElementById(blah);
    }
}
</pre>
<p>
NOTE: IE uses a different name for the object.
<pre>req = new ActiveXOjbect("Microsoft.XMLHTTP");</pre>
</p>
<p>
Much more information <a href="http://developer.apple.com/internet/webcontent/xmlhttpreq.html">available</a>.
</p>
<div class="handout">
<p>
This example doesn't work in IE.
You must check for IE and if so set differently.
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Does it have to XML responses?</h1>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.json.org/">JSON</a> (JavaScript Object Notation)</li>
<ul>
<li>Instead of passing heavy XML objects just pass JavaScript</li>
<li>ex: {'varname':'value','varname2':'value2'}</li>
<li>No DOM parsing! Just use the JavaScript eval function</li>
</ul>
<li>HTML (format the response on the server)</li>
<li>TEXT (the easy way out)</li>
<li>XML (Intended Use)</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Example</h1>
<ul>
<li>As an example lets build a little rating feature</li>
<li>A little PHP as the back-end</li>
<li>Javascript to send the users votes back to the server</li>
<li>Javascript to modify the DOM tree to give the user
feedback</li>
<li>Inspired from Netflix and Amazon Rating system</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>The Bad Stuff</h1>
<ul>
<li>Breaks back button</li>
<li>Cross-browser support</li>
<li>Security at the browser can cause your application to break</li>
<li>Only able to request from the same server the page loaded from</li>
<li>Lots more code to do simple tasks (similar to threaded code vs
non-thread)</li>
<li>Pooling for data instead of being notified</li>
<li>Interpreted Language - Sending your precious code to the
client</li>
<li>Is this really robust?</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Options anyone?</h1>
<ul>
<li>Java Applets</li>
<li>Flash</li>
<li>Active-X</li>
<li>SVG</li>
<li>XUL - Mozilla</li>
<li>XAML - Microsoft</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Libraries</h1>
<ul>
<li>Javascript libraries being generated</li>
<ol>
<li><a href="http://mochikit.com/">Mochikit</a> - provides DOM scripting and AJAX helpers (python inspired)</li>
<li><a href="http://dojotoolkit.org/">DOJO</a> - Browser Widget and Messaging System</li>
</ol>
<li>Complete frameworks server and client</li>
<ol>
<li><a href="http://www.rubyonrails.org/">Ruby on Rails</a> - Provides
server and tight integration with data store</li>
<li><a href="http://www.turbogears.org/">TurboGears</a> - Python stack similar to ruby on rails</li>
<li><a href="http://www.nextapp.com/platform/echo2/echo/">Echo 2</a> - Java framework</li>
<li><a href="http://atlas.asp.net/">Atlas</a> - Microsoft ASP.net</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
<h1>Is it more than buzz?</h1>
<ul>
<li>Open Standards</li>
<li>Not vendor locked</li>
<li>Built upon existing technology</li>
<li>Service Oriented Architecture is proven</li>
<li>Everyone expects Google</li>
<li>Business Case for Usability</li>
</ul>
</div>


